<p>To use an SVG as an include:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Add the SVG to the <code class="highlighter-rouge">/_includes/svg/</code> directory.</li>
  <li>In an include tag, reference the file path of the SVG relative to the <code class="highlighter-rouge">_includes</code> directory.</li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Accessibility</strong></p>

<p>To follow <a href="https://guides.18f.gov/accessibility/">accessibility guidelines</a>, make sure that the SVG image file contains all the necessary markup to allow screenreader users to browse your site without difficulty. From the <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/SVG-access/#Equivalent">WCAG guidlines</a> on creating accessibile SVGs:</p>

<ul>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">title</code>: Provides a human-readable title for the element that contains it. The <code class="highlighter-rouge">title</code> element may be rendered by a graphical user agent as a tooltip. It may be rendered as speech by a speech synthesizer.</li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">desc</code>: Provides a longer more complete description of an element that contains it. Authors should provide descriptions for complex or other content that has functional meaning.</li>
</ul>

<p>If the SVG is a presentation only image, meaning that it is assistive, but not necessary to provide context within the site, add the following attributes to the <code class="highlighter-rouge">svg</code> tag itself:</p>

<ul>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">role="img"</code></li>
  <li><code class="highlighter-rouge">aria-hidden="true"</code></li>
</ul>
